        ],
        "date": "2026-07-20",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-20T15:10:04.319Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz entered Monday under compounding pressure from multiple fronts. The most operationally significant development: Yemen's Ansarullah movement declared a full naval blockade against Saudi Arabia, per Iranian state media IRNA and Mehr News, framing it as reciprocal action for what it describes as nearly 12 years of siege on Yemen. Neither claim has been independently confirmed, and no Western or Saudi government source has corroborated the blockade's enforcement. Separately, gCaptain reports that an oil tanker halted in the strait after the Iranian Navy targeted vessels in the waterway, adding to a backlog that stood at 446 vessels anchored or stopped as of this morning. PortWatch's most recent published data, covering 2026-07-12, recorded 10 transits through the strait against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day; scraper-derived 24-hour arrivals at Gulf ports reached 550, though the two figures use different methodologies and cannot be directly compared. Brent crude traded at $88.46 at the time of writing, up +0.41% over 24 hours, a muted reaction relative to the severity of reported disruptions. The Hormuz Index Crisis Pressure composite remains in the extreme band, flat over 24 hours, with physical transit deviation as the top contributor. The 30-day Escalation Forecast sits in the elevated band and is rising, driven primarily by Polymarket closure odds, a divergence from the flat state composite that warrants close attention from risk desks.",
        "transitsToday": 10
    },
